entry.title: Gonocarpus humilis
entry.content: One straggly plant on a dry creek. New species record for Conglomerate Gully and Riddells Creek.

entry.title: Solenogyne dominii
entry.content: Leaf is glabrous and number of teeth fit dominii, whereas peduncle is hirsute as in gunnii.

entry.title: Montia fontana
entry.content: ID to species by Neville Walsh. New species record for the Macedon Range. Growing in a trickle/seepage on rocks in an ephemeral part of the creek. Flowers tiny. Bifid style. Looks like a petal is missing but all flowers are like this - Levenhookia-like. Looks like 3 or 4 bilobed/notched petals.

entry.content: New species record for Conglomerate Gully. Found on track leaving open area right above waterfall and between the two entrances to the viewing platform.

entry.title: Mazus pumilio
entry.content: New species record for Riddells Creek.

entry.title: Calandrinia calyptrata
entry.content: A few plants surviving in rock crevices.

entry.title: Hydrocotyle sibthorpioides
entry.content: 2m mat in dried up flow area of upper reaches of creek. Frill of hairs at top of leaf stem (pic 3). Leaves glabrescent/shining above (only long fine hairs on upper surface) and some hairs visible on leaf under-surface. New species for Riddell.

entry.title: Ranunculus glabrifolius
entry.content: Fruit and leaf seem to confirm species. New species record for Riddells Creek.

entry.title: Hypericum spp.
entry.content: Possibly H. japonicum. Large patch in dried up flow area of upper reaches of creek. Small flowers compared to gramineum plants in drier areas nearby. Would be a new species record for Riddells Creek.

entry.title: Cassytha glabella f. dispar
entry.content: New species record for Conglomerate Gully.

entry.title: Triglochin spp.
entry.content: What an underwater Triglochin rootall looks like when its pool has dried up.

entry.title: Epacris impressa var. impressa
entry.content: Plants are looking quite distraught after the dry weather, many are dead and those surviving have leaves just in clusters along woody stems.

entry.title: Cheilanthes austrotenuifolia
entry.content: Suffered badly this year with considerable die back but they are returning very well.

entry.title: Hypoxis hygrometrica var. villosisepala
entry.content: New species record for CGully. Pics show all ID features for this variety - sepals hairy externally, anthers bifid apically & basally, flowers often 2 per peduncle.

entry.title: Pauridia glabella var. glabella
entry.content: Lots flowering today. Flora of Victoria has it flowering Jul-Sep. 2nd pic shows the two sheathing bracteoles at base of flowering stem.

entry.title: Pelargonium rodneyanum
entry.content: Hundreds of plants but only a couple of flowers.

entry.title: Tricoryne elatior
entry.content: New species record for Conglomerate Gully. Seen lots around Riddells Creek and nearby towns in the past two weeks.

entry.title: Rytidosperma pallidum
entry.content: Seems to be flowering earlier than usual?

entry.title: Triglochin striata
entry.content: Growing among Gratiola peruviana on the edge of a pond that is slowly drying up.

entry.title: Gratiola peruviana
entry.content: In an area usually waterlogged - edge of a pool.

entry.title: Leucochrysum albicans var. albicans
entry.content: Note small moths on 2nd pic (Glyphiptera or Oecophorid moths perhaps).

entry.title: Leucochrysum albicans var. albicans, Turneriprocris dolens
entry.content: Moth is about half the size of the similar-looking Satin-green Forester, which was also about in large numbers this day (see following observation, 7803). T. dolens seen primarily on the Leucochrysum.

entry.title: 3 ids
entry.content: Nice spot with three fern species growing together out of a rock face. The large leaves are Pelargonium rodneyanum.

entry.title: Cheilanthes sieberi subsp. sieberi
entry.content: Lots of plants on a small rocky area in the forest.

entry.title: Lomandra filiformis
entry.content: Good population of the grey-leaved form of Lomandra filiformis. Leaves range from 2mm wide upwards. Right on the imaginary border of Barrm Birrm and Conglomerate Gully.

entry.content: 75 individuals in this picture.
